entation of NICE clinical guidelines and quality standards. The new national clinical audit will be in place by the end of 2014-15.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","201409","2014-06-26T14:34:49.6007856Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62926/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62926/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62926/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-06-19","Breast Cancer","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what guidance his Department gives to clinical commissioning groups on commissioning breast cancer services.","false","Biography information for Andrew Bridgen","North West Leicestershire","Andrew Bridgen","201405"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62927","Department of Health","false","2014-06-26","<p>Public Health England is not responsible for policy on cancer, but does ensure the delivery of several cancer related functions including NHS Cancer Screening Programmes, Be Clear on Cancer campaigns, cancer screening quality assurance, the National Cancer Intelligence Network and the National Cancer Registration Service. National strategic oversight and policy on cancer screening, early diagnosis and cancer informatics remains with the Department with 3.5 whole time equivalent posts.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","201403","2014-06-26T14:12:28.5253066Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62927/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62927/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62927/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-06-19","Cancer","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what responsibilities for cancer policy that were previously within the remit of his Department are now held by Public Health England staff.","false","Biography information for Andrew Bridgen","North West Leicestershire","Andrew Bridgen","201406"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62928","Department of Health","false","2014-06-26","<p>Officials from the Department, Public Health England (PHE) and NHS England are currently discussing how hepatitis C services might be strengthened, including how local Health and Wellbeing Boards can be encouraged to include hepatitis C in their Joint Strategic Needs Assessments, where appropriate. The findings of the HCV Action report will help to inform those discussions.</p><p> </p><p>PHE is developing local profiles that include indicators of performance for hepatitis C which are aimed at local authorities and Health and Wellbeing Boards. These profiles include a summary of the issues around hepatitis C including those most at risk, as well as questions for Health and Wellbeing Boards to ask about local provision of hepatitis C services. PHE has produced a fact sheet for the Local Government Association on hepatitis B and C to support their scrutiny and oversight role.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","201560","2014-06-26T15:37:06.4434283Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62928/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62928/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62928/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-06-19","Hepatitis","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps his Department is taking to ensure that areas with a high prevalence of hepatitis C include measures to tackle the virus within their joint strategic needs assessments.","false","Biography information for Mr Virendra Sharma","Ealing, Southall","Mr Virendra Sharma","201563"
