"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62674","Home Office","false","2014-06-30","<p> </p><p>The Home Secretary laid two reports before Parliament on 19 June 2014, <br>that had been supplied by the Independent Chief Inspector of Borders and <br>Immigration pursuant to sections 50 (2) and 50 (3) of the UK Borders Act 2007:<br><br>- An unannounced inspection of the service provided by Glasgow Public Enquiry <br>Office, ID 13061402 06/14.<br><br>- The rights of European Citizens and their spouses to come to the UK: <br>inspecting the application process and the tackling of abuse, ID 2634429 04/14.<br><br>Four further reports have been supplied by the Chief Inspector that will be <br>published shortly.</p><p> </p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2014-06-30T12:41:50.7857025Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62674/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62674/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62674/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-06-18","Independent Chief Inspector of Borders and Immigration","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, which completed reports from the Independent Chief Inspector of Borders and Immigration have been submitted for publication but had not yet been published on 17 June 2014; and what the (a) date of submission and (b) date she expects to publish the report is in each case.","false","Biography information for David Hanson","Delyn","Mr David Hanson","201384"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62675","Home Office","false","2014-06-25","<p> </p><p>The table below shows the number of calls received by the Metropolitan Police <br>human trafficking hotline since it was set up in June 2011. <br><br>Year Number of calls<br>2014 29 (to 19 June)<br>2013 41<br>2012 52<br>2011 34 (June to December)<br><br>The freephone hotline number (0800 783 2589) is funded by Stop The Traffik and <br>therefore has no cost to the Metropolitan Police Service other than the £15 per <br>month line rental.</p><p> </p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2014-06-25T13:09:22.7262959Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62675/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62675/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62675/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-06-18","Human Trafficking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many calls the Metropolitan Police human trafficking hotline received from victims of human trafficking in each of the last three years; and what the annual cost of running the hotline is.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Mr Frank Field","201396"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62676","Home Office","false","2014-06-30","<p> </p><p>Home Office Ministers and officials have meetings with a wide variety of <br>international partners, as well as organisations and individuals in the public <br>and private sectors, as part of the process of policy development and delivery. <br>Details of Ministerial meetings with external organisations and individuals are <br>passed to the Cabinet Office on a quarterly basis and are subsequently <br>published on the Cabinet Office website which is available here: <br>https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/home-office-ministers-gifts-and-hospi<br>tality-oct-2012-to-dec-2012</p><p> </p>","Lewes","Norman Baker",,"2014-06-30T16:19:02.499428Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62676/answer","Biography information for Norman Baker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62676/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62676/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-06-18","NSPCC","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many meetings have taken place since the beginning of 2014 between departmental officials and the NSPCC; who attended such meetings; what the purpose was of such meetings; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Mr Frank Field","201397"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62677","Home Office","false","2014-07-22","<p> </p><p> </p><p>In June 2014, (a) 59, 692 people applied and paid for fast track and (b) 31, <br>289 applied for premium service. Her Majesty's Passport Office (HMPO) only <br>normally offer compensation for financial loss as a result of delays in their guaranteed<br>(Fast Track and Premium) services. HMPO does not have an estimate of how much <br>compensation may be paid this year in line with their policy. As the Home <br>Secretary announced on 12 June 2014, customers who need to travel within 7 days and who <br>have waited more than the three weeks service standard for a straightforward application to <br>be processed through no fault of their own, are fast-tracked free of charge. <br>To 15 July, HMPO has issued 13, 461 passports as a result of this change of <br>policy.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2014-07-22T14:45:19.6890822Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62677/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62677/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62677/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-06-18","Passports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what estimate she has made of the number of people who have applied for passports using the (a) fast track and (b) premium service in the last month; and how many recent passport applications will receive compensation from her Department.","false","Biography information for Pete Wishart","Perth and North Perthshire","Pete Wishart","201354"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62678","Home Office","false","2014-07-14","<p> </p><p>Her Majesty's Passport Office do not collect this data.</p><p> </p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2014-07-14T16:14:42.5249795Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62678/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62678/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62678/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-06-18","Passports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what estimate she has made of the number of people who cancelled holidays in 2014 due to delays in passport applications.","false","Biography information for Pete Wishart","Perth and North Perthshire","Pete Wishart","201355"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62679","Home Office","false","2014-07-07","<p> </p><p>No passport offices have been closed in the last five years.<br>Restructuring of passport operations between 2010 and 2012 entailed the closure <br>of some interview offices and relocation of the Newport passport office. These <br>changes realised annual savings of approximately £7.2 million per year.<br><br>We do not collect data on the costs of cancelled and altered flights</p><p> </p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2014-07-07T15:24:31.2703429Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62679/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62679/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62679/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-06-18","HM Passport Office","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what estimate she has made of the savings generated by closing passport offices in the last five years; and what estimate she has made of the total cost of (a) cancelled and (b) altered flights due to delayed passport applications in 2014.","false","Biography information for Pete Wishart","Perth and North Perthshire","Pete Wishart","201357"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62680","Home Office","false","2014-06-30","<p> </p><p>Her Majesty's Passport Office does not consider that changes in its office in <br>Glasgow have had any impact on the speed of processing applications for passports.</p><p> </p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2014-06-30T15:29:22.2899401Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62680/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62680/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62680/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-06-18","HM Passport Office: Glasgow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment she has made of the effect of changes in the number of staff in the Glasgow Passport Office since 2008 on the speed of the processing of applications for passports by that office.","false","Biography information for Pete Wishart","Perth and North Perthshire","Pete Wishart","201356"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62681","Home Office","false","2014-06-30","<p> </p><p>Each year Her Majesty's Passport Office plans its capacity, taking into account <br>the likely level of demand during specific periods, including the run-up to school <br>holidays.</p><p> </p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2014-06-30T15:25:44.7752325Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62681/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62681/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62681/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-06-18","Passports: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what account her Department took of the timing of school holidays in Scotland in formulating plans to deal with passport application delays.","false","Biography information for Pete Wishart","Perth and North Perthshire","Pete Wishart","201352"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62682","Home Office","false","2014-07-08","<p> </p><p>Her Majesty's Passport Office began recording data on complaints and compensation paid by various categories in 2005 so data is not held relating to 2004. Compensation paid to <br>passport applicants relating to complaints concerning application processing <br>delays amounted to:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>2005</p></td><td><p>£13,064</p></td></tr><tr><td> </td><td> </td></tr><tr><td><p>2006</p></td><td><p>£18,684</p></td></tr><tr><td> </td><td> </td></tr><tr><td><p>2007</p></td><td><p>£1,888</p></td></tr><tr><td> </td><td> </td></tr><tr><td><p>2008</p></td><td><p>£2,090</p></td></tr><tr><td> </td><td> </td></tr><tr><td><p>2009</p></td><td><p>£1,504</p></td></tr><tr><td> </td><td> </td></tr><tr><td><p>2010</p></td><td><p>£11,978</p></td></tr><tr><td> </td><td> </td></tr><tr><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>£933</p></td></tr><tr><td> </td><td> </td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>£2,999</p></td></tr><tr><td> </td><td> </td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>£1,445</p></td></tr><tr><td> </td><td> </td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2014-07-08T14:13:38.814634Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62682/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62682/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62682/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-06-18","Passports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how much HM Passport Office has paid in compensation for delays in customers receiving passports in each year since 2004.","false","Biography information for Pete Wishart","Perth and North Perthshire","Pete Wishart","201353"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62683","Home Office","false","2014-06-23","<p> </p><p>The available information requested is given in the table below:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="2"><em>Family entry clearance visas issued, by category.</em></td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td></tr><tr><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td></tr><tr><td><strong>Visa Category</strong></td><td><strong>2011</strong></td><td><strong>2012</strong></td><td><strong>2013</strong></td><td><strong>Q1 2014 (Jan-Mar)</strong></td></tr><tr><td>Family: Partner</td><td>33,496</td><td>30,411</td><td>23,557</td><td>6,825</td></tr><tr><td>Family: Child</td><td>97</td><td>85</td><td>73</td><td>16</td></tr><tr><td>Family: Other</td><td>4,306</td><td>3,710</td><td>4,233</td><td>1,591</td></tr><tr><td>Family: Partner (for immediate settlement)</td><td>1,336</td><td>1,097</td><td>1,084</td><td>176</td></tr><tr><td>Family: Child (for immediate settlement)</td><td>4,596</td><td>4,001</td><td>3,844</td><td>726</td></tr><tr><td>Family: Other (for immediate settlement)</td><td>1,892</td><td>1,588</td><td>899</td><td>296</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Total</strong></td><td><strong>45,723</strong></td><td><strong>40,892</strong></td><td><strong>33,690</strong></td><td><strong>9,630</strong></td></tr><tr><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td></tr><tr><td colspan="5"><em>Source: Immigration Statistics, January-March 2014, Before Entry Volume 2, table be_01_q</em></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>The Home Office publishes quarterly statistics on entry clearance visa grants <br>by category in table be_01_q (Before Entry tables volume 2) within the <br>‘Immigration Statistics' release. The numbers are broken down by nationality in <br>table be_06_q_f (Before Entry tables volume 4). It is not possible to <br>separately identify those granted visas under the old family rules and those <br>granted visas under new family rules implemented on 9 July 2012.<br><br>A copy of the latest release, ‘Immigration Statistics January - March 2014' is <br>available from the Library of the House and from: <br>https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/home-office/series/immigration-stati<br>stics-quarterly-release. <br><br>The figures provided relate to family members issued visas in the family <br>immigration route. Statistics on the dependants of migrants issued visas in <br>other routes, such as the Points Based System, can be found within the <br>published data at the above link.<br><br>The information requested in part (ii) on the UK nation of residence of the <br>sponsor of each of the family visas of interest is not readily available and <br>could only be obtained at disproportionate cost. Furthermore, not all sponsors <br>are based in the UK and not all individuals granted a visa in the family route <br>have a sponsor.</p><p> </p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2014-06-23T11:27:58.4523131Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62683/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62683/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62683/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-06-18","Entry Clearances","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many family visas were granted (a) in each year since 2011 and (b) in the current year up to the latest available quarter for which figures are available; and what the (i) category of family visa and (ii) UK nation of residence of the sponsor of each such visa was.","false","Biography information for Angus Brendan MacNeil","Na h-Eileanan an Iar","Mr Angus Brendan MacNeil","201341"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62684","Home Office","false","2014-06-23","<p> </p><p>The Home Office does not hold this information.</p><p>The police have the power under the Road Traffic Act (1988) to seize vehicles <br>driven without insurance. Enforcement of vehicle seizures is an operational matter for the police.</p><p> </p>","Ashford","Damian Green",,"2014-06-23T11:34:13.8832439Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62684/answer","Biography information for Damian Green","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62684/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62684/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-06-18","Driving Offences: Insurance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many vehicles were seized by the police as a result of being driven without insurance in (a) Dartford constituency and (b) England and Wales in each of the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Gareth Johnson","Dartford","Gareth Johnson","201324"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62685","Home Office","false","2014-06-30","<p> </p><p>Her Majesty's Passport Office does not store information at constituency level <br>and the cost of extracting the information requested would be disproportionate. <br>Information on passport processing performance can be found in HMPO's annual <br>report and accounts, which can be accessed via the links below. <br><br>2009-2010:<br>https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/118758<br>/annual-report-accounts-200910.pdf<br><br>2010-2011:<br>https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/identity-and-passport-service-annual-<br>report-and-accounts-2010-to-2011<br><br>2011-2012:<br>https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/118751<br>/ips-annual-report-2012.pdf<br><br>2012-2013:<br>https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/210619<br>/IPS_annual_report_and_accounts_2012-13.pdf</p><p> </p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2014-06-30T15:30:55.9219464Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62685/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62685/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62685/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-06-18","Passports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what estimate she has made of the number of passports that were issued for residents of (a) Airdrie and Shotts constituency, (b) Lanarkshire, (c) Scotland and (d) the UK in each year since 2009.","false","Biography information for Pamela Nash","Airdrie and Shotts","Pamela Nash","201271"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62686","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-06-23","<p>I am responding to this question as I am the Minister responsible for the prison estate. We are well aware of the risks posed by individuals who return to the UK having gained experience, through training or participation, in terrorism overseas. At the current time clearly those travelling to and from Syria are of particular concern.</p><p> </p><p>The Prison Service works closely with the Police and other Agencies in all areas of Counter Terrorism work; including where individuals are held in custody having returned from overseas. All prisoners are managed according to the risk they pose, taking into consideration all relevant information and intelligence that is identified.</p><p> </p><p>The National Offender Management Service (NOMS) has long recognised the threat posed by terrorists and extremists, and has considerable experience in managing this threat. The Prison Service will continue to use its well established and effective three-tiered response: to identify behaviour that may indicate extremism, to report it using established intelligence systems, and to manage it through disruption and intervention.</p><p> </p>","Kenilworth and Southam","Jeremy Wright",,"2014-06-23T16:28:23.1386556Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62686/answer","Biography information for Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62686/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62686/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-06-18","Prisoners: Radicalism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what assessment his Department has made of the potential risks of imprisoned extremists returned from terrorist operations overseas (a) radicalising the Muslim prison population and (b) recruiting other prisoners to commit terrorist acts in the UK or overseas.","false","Biography information for Dr Liam Fox","North Somerset","Dr Liam Fox","201336"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62687","Home Office","false","2014-07-22","<p> </p><p> </p><p>Her Majesty's Passport Office does not log performance data at office, regional <br>or home country level. Performance is monitored at a national level as Her <br>Majesty's Passport Office distributes work across the UK estate to manage <br>variation in local levels of passport demand. The cost of identifying the information<br>in the format requested would be disproportionate.<br><br>Information on the number of passports issued each year in the UK is set out in <br>Her Majesty's Passport Office's Annual Report and Accounts. I refer to the <br>Answer given to the hon. Member on 30 June 2014, Official Report, column 381W. <br><br>Her Majesty'sPassport Office have issued over 4 million passports in the year <br>2014 to date.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2014-07-22T14:52:12.8063839Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62687/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62687/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62687/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-06-18","HM Passport Office","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what performance indicators for the renewal of existing passports have been met by each passport office administrative centre in (a) Scotland, (b) Wales, (c) Northern Ireland and (d) England in each year since 2009.","false","Biography information for Pamela Nash","Airdrie and Shotts","Pamela Nash","201273"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62688","Home Office","false","2014-06-30","<p> </p><p>The Home Secretary is giving fresh consideration to the exercise of her <br>discretion to establish an inquiry following the Court of Appeal's judgment of <br>14 February 2014 relating to Mr. Litvinenko. Once this is concluded, a <br>statement will be made. In the meantime, the Government continues to co-operate <br>fully with the Inquest into Mr Litvinenko's death.</p><p> </p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2014-06-30T12:38:57.8090834Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62688/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62688/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62688/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-06-18","Alexander Litvinenko","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, when she expects to conclude her consideration of the Coroner's ruling in the case of Alexander Litvinenko; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Evans","Cardiff North","Jonathan Evans","201276"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62689","Home Office","false","2014-06-25","<p> </p><p>The information requested is not available.<br><br>Data on arrests are reported to the Home Office on the basis of aggregated <br>offence categories only, for example violence against the person, sexual <br>offences and robbery. From these centrally reported categories it is not <br>possible to separately identify arrests that involve domestic violence.</p><p> </p>","Lewes","Norman Baker",,"2014-06-25T13:07:54.0143812Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62689/answer","Biography information for Norman Baker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62689/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62689/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-06-18","Domestic Abuse: Dartford","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what estimate she has made of the number of (a) arrests and (b) convictions for domestic violence offences in Dartford constituency in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Gareth Johnson","Dartford","Gareth Johnson","201302"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62690","Home Office","false","2014-06-30","<p> </p><p>A straightforward application is one where all the required information, <br>including supporting documentation, is provided, the application is signed and <br>no further enquiries are required in order to progress the application.</p><p> </p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2014-06-30T15:28:06.5967482Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62690/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62690/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62690/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-06-18","HM Passport Office","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what definition is used by HM Passport Office of a straightforward application for passports for the purpose of setting internal targets; and if this definition has been amended since 2010.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","201301"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62691","Home Office","false","2014-06-30","<p> </p><p>UK Visas and Immigration offer the following numbers for members of the public <br>wishing to make enquiries<br><br>Number<br>Service<br>0300 123 2253<br>European and Nationality related enquiries<br>0300 123 2235<br>Asylum Support Customers<br>0300 123 2241<br>General enquiries<br>0300 123 4699<br>Sponsor and employer helpline</p><p> </p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2014-06-30T13:40:41.7768229Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62691/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62691/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62691/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-06-18","UK Visas and Immigration","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether an 0300 telephone line is available for people wishing to make enquiries of UK Visas and Immigration.","false","Biography information for Baroness McIntosh of Pickering","Thirsk and Malton","Miss Anne McIntosh","201295"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62692","Home Office","false","2014-06-30","<p> </p><p>Her Majesty's Passport Office does not store information at constituency level <br>and the cost of extracting the information requested would be disproportionate. <br>Information on passport processing performance can be found in HMPO's annual <br>report and accounts, which can be accessed via the links below. <br><br>2009-2010:<br>https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/118758<br>/annual-report-accounts-200910.pdf<br><br>2010-2011:<br>https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/identity-and-passport-service-annual-<br>report-and-accounts-2010-to-2011<br><br>2011-2012:<br>https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/118751<br>/ips-annual-report-2012.pdf<br><br>2012-2013:<br>https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/210619<br>/IPS_annual_report_and_accounts_2012-13.pdf</p><p> </p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2014-06-30T15:33:36.8201553Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62692/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62692/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62692/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-06-18","Passports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what estimate she has made of the average time period between application and issuing of passports for residents of (a) Airdrie and Shotts constituency, (b) Lanarkshire, (c) Scotland and (d) the UK in each year since 2009.","false","Biography information for Pamela Nash","Airdrie and Shotts","Pamela Nash","201268"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62693","Home Office","false","2014-07-09","<p> </p><p>Her Majesty's Passport Office (HMPO) does not store information at constituency level and <br>the cost of extracting the information requested would be disproportionate. <br>Information on passport processing performance can be found in HMPO's annual <br>report and accounts, via the links below. <br><br>2009-2010:<br>https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/118758<br>/annual-report-accounts-200910.pdf<br><br>2010-2011:<br>https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/identity-and-passport-service-annual-<br>report-and-accounts-2010-to-2011<br><br>2011-2012:<br>https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/118751<br>/ips-annual-report-2012.pdf<br><br>2012-2013:<br>https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/210619<br>/IPS_annual_report_and_accounts_2012-13.pdf</p><p> </p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2014-07-09T12:36:45.7426893Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62693/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62693/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62693/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-06-18","Passports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many passport renewals for residents in (a) Airdrie and Shotts constituency, (b) Lanarkshire, (c) Scotland and (d) the UK have been completed within a three week turnaround time from receipt in each year since 2009.","false","Biography information for Pamela Nash","Airdrie and Shotts","Pamela Nash","201269"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62694","Home Office","false","2014-06-30","<p> </p><p>We are aware that some UK Visas and Immigration letters may still contain the <br>0870 contact number, and this is being addressed. A small number of <br>representations have been received on this matter.</p><p> </p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2014-06-30T11:22:13.4508409Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62694/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62694/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62694/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-06-18","UK Visas and Immigration","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what recent representations she has received on the incorrect 0870 telephone number being given out to applicants seeking advice on their applications with UK Visas and Immigration; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Baroness McIntosh of Pickering","Thirsk and Malton","Miss Anne McIntosh","201321"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62695","House of Commons Commission","false","2014-06-24","<p>There are no immediate plans to change the current method of connection. PICT is aware of the restriction that the current arrangement places on users, and will look afresh at the authentication needed for known users of the guest Wi-Fi service, “Internet Direct”.</p>","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","John Thurso",,"2014-06-24T10:20:07.4749405Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62695/answer","Biography information for Viscount Thurso","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62695/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62695/answer",,,,,"18","House of Commons Commission","House of Commons Commission","2014-06-18","Parliament: WiFi","1","House of Commons","To ask the hon. Member for Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross representing the House of Commons Commission, whether the Commission plans to modify the Parliamentary wifi system to enable automatic log-in by BlackBerry and other devices without the need to enter a username and password manually each time.","false","Biography information for Michael Fabricant","Lichfield","Michael Fabricant","201348"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62696","Department for International Development","false","2014-06-25","<p>The Conflict Pool is funded from an HM Treasury settlement which is separate from and additional to departmental budgets. Details of Conflict Pool allocations are provided to Parliament annually in a Written Ministerial Statement. The statements for Financial Years 2011/12, 2012/13 and 2013/14 are available on the parliament.uk website.</p><p> </p><p>A Statement giving details of Conflict Pool allocations for FY 2014/15 will be laid before the House shortly.</p><p> </p>","Rutland and Melton","Mr Alan Duncan",,"2014-06-25T14:58:26.1193154Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62696/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62696/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62696/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2014-06-18","South Asia","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how much funding her Department allocated to the Conflict Pool for South Asia in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Mr Bob Ainsworth","Coventry North East","Mr Bob Ainsworth","201189"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62697","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-06-24","<p /> <p /> <p>Staff in the National Probation Service (NPS) and the Community Rehabilitation Companies (CRCs) have, and will continue to have, necessary access to each other's case records. NPS staff are able to read all CRC records and update any case they are working on. CRC staff will be able to see and update records that relate to offenders they are working with.</p>","Kenilworth and Southam","Jeremy Wright","201208","2014-06-24T15:08:19.4532042Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62697/answer","Biography information for Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62697/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62697/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-06-18","Community Rehabilitation Companies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, whether community rehabilitation companies have access to National Probation Service case records.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","201206"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62698","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-06-25","<p>G4S and Serco decided to withdraw from the competition to select lead providers of rehabilitation services.</p>","Kenilworth and Southam","Jeremy Wright",,"2014-06-25T16:45:58.0076129Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62698/answer","Biography information for Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62698/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62698/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-06-18","Community Rehabilitation Companies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, whether (a) Serco and (b) G4S will be permitted to bid for community rehabilitation company contracts.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","201207"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62699","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-06-24","<p /> <p /> <p>On 1 June, as part of our ongoing Transforming Rehabilitation Programme of reform, the new National Probation Service (NPS) and Community Rehabilitation Companies (CRCs) formally commenced operation. All probation staff were allocated to either the NPS or CRC and many have been working in their new teams since April.</p><p> </p><p>The probation workforce was allocated to the new organisations in line with future capacity needs. This was calculated on the basis of existing staffing needs for the different operational functions. The process was based on an objective consideration of the future functions and offender groups that each organisation will be responsible for.</p><p> </p><p>There are no plans to allocate NPS staff to CRCs. However to help ensure effective working relationships between the bodies, we are in favour of an arrangement that would facilitate interchange between the NPS and CRCs where it was in the interests of both employers.</p>","Kenilworth and Southam","Jeremy Wright",,"2014-06-24T15:17:22.1714826Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62699/answer","Biography information for Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62699/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62699/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-06-18","Community Rehabilitation Companies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how he plans to allocate National Probation Service staff to new community rehabilitation companies.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","201196"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62700","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-06-24","<p /> <p /> <p>Staff in the National Probation Service (NPS) and the Community Rehabilitation Companies (CRCs) have, and will continue to have, necessary access to each other's case records. NPS staff are able to read all CRC records and update any case they are working on. CRC staff will be able to see and update records that relate to offenders they are working with.</p>","Kenilworth and Southam","Jeremy Wright","201206","2014-06-24T15:08:19.559056Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62700/answer","Biography information for Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62700/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62700/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-06-18","Community Rehabilitation Companies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, whether the National Probation Service will have access to case records of community rehabilitation companies.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","201208"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62701","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-06-25","<p>The decision whether to recall an offender to custody continues to rest with the Secretary of State. Where a warning does not appear sufficient or appropriate, CRCs will be required to refer potential breaches to the National Offender Management Service (NOMS) with a breach report and a recommendation on the action to be taken. NOMS will take the final decision on behalf of the Secretary of State. The enforcement process for CRCs and the National Probation Service was described in detail in our published Target Operating Model.</p><p> </p><p>Offenders serving indeterminate sentences for public protection will be managed by the National Probation Service: the arrangements for Parole Board hearings during their recall period will remain unchanged. If recalled to custody, offenders allocated to the CRCs who are serving determinate sentences will continue to be managed by the CRC, unless their risk of serious harm increases to “high”. CRCs will need to provide information, as appropriate, to support the recall process and consideration of re-release.</p>","Kenilworth and Southam","Jeremy Wright",,"2014-06-25T16:43:34.8001888Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62701/answer","Biography information for Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62701/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62701/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-06-18","Community Rehabilitation Companies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, whether staff working for community rehabilitation companies will be able to (a) recall offenders and (b) write parole reports without consulting National Probation Service staff.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","201199"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62702","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-06-24","<p /> <p /> <p>The tendering process is being run in accordance with standard Government procurement practice. Ministers are being kept updated on progress and throughout the programme have engaged in discussions with a wide range of stakeholders. Bids to run the Community Rehabilitation Companies (CRCs) are expected in June 2014 and the contract winners for each Community Rehabilitation Company will be announced by the end of 2014.</p>","Kenilworth and Southam","Jeremy Wright",,"2014-06-24T15:05:55.3853008Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62702/answer","Biography information for Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62702/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62702/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-06-18","Community Rehabilitation Companies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what recent discussions he has had on tendering for contracts to run community rehabilitation companies.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","201204"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62703","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-06-26","<p> </p><p> </p><p>The number of offenders cautioned and defendants proceeded against at magistrates’ courts and found guilty at all courts for offences (all in England and Wales from 2009 to 2013) under the Game Act 1831 can be viewed in Table 1, under the Deer Act 1991 in Table 2, under the Protection of Badgers act 1992 in Table 3, under the Wildlife and Countryside Act 1981 in Table 4, under the Wild Mammals (Protection) Act 1996 in Table 5, under the Animal Welfare Act 2006 in Table 6, under the Conservation of Seals Act 1970 in Table 7, under the Night Poaching Act 1828 in Table 8, under the Control of Trade in Endangered Species (Enforcement) Regulations 1997 in Table 9, under the Hunting Act 2004 in Table 10 and under the Conservation of Habitats and Species Regulations 2010 in Table 11. The tables can be found in the Library. Data for the Pests Act 1954, the Dangerous Wild Animals Act 1976 and the Conservation (Natural Habitats) Regulations 1994 is held as part of a miscellaneous group that cannot be separately analysed.We are very clear that serious offences will always go to court where tough punishments are available to the independent judiciary, who make their sentencing decisions based on the individual facts of the case.</p><p> </p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2014-06-26T10:26:26.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62703/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62703/answer","201202.xls","201202.xls","Misc offender numbers - caution and court","Misc offender numbers - caution and court","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62703/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-06-18","Crime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many people were (a) cautioned, (b) proceeded against and (c) convicted of an offence under the provisions of the (i) Game Act 1831, (ii) Deer Act 1991, (iii) Protection of Badgers Act 1992, (iv) Wildlife and Countryside Act 1981, (v) Wild Mammals (Protection) Act 1996, (vi) Animal Welfare Act 2006, (vii) Conservation (Natural Habitats) Regulations 1994 and Conservation of Habitats and Species Regulations 2010, (viii) Hunting Act 2004, (ix) Night Poaching Act 1828, (x) Control of Trade in Endangered Species (Enforcement) Regulations 1997, (xi) Dangerous Wild Animals Act 1976, (xii) Pests Act 1954 and (xiii) Conservation of Seals Act 1970 in each year since 2009.","false","Biography information for Jim Fitzpatrick","Poplar and Limehouse","Jim Fitzpatrick","201202"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62704","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-06-23","<p>Prior to 1 June, probation staff in England &amp; Wales were employed by the 35 probation trusts. Employment data of the kind requested were held by the individual probations trusts. They were not collected centrally and it would not be possible to obtain the information without incurring disproportionate cost.</p>","Kenilworth and Southam","Jeremy Wright","201232 ; 201236","2014-06-23T16:32:11.3671937Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62704/answer","Biography information for Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62704/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62704/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-06-18","Probation Trusts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many former employees of probation trusts received payouts of (a) up to £5,000, (b) up to £10,0000, (c) up to £15,000, (d) up to £20,000, (e) up to £30,000, (f) up to £40,000, (g) up to £50,000, (h) up to £75,000, (i) up to £100,000 or (j) £100,000 or more since 1 January 2014.","false","Biography information for Sadiq Khan","Tooting","Sadiq Khan","201231"
