ment.uk/resources/62207/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62207/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2014-06-17","Financial Services","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the effects of the shadow banking sector on the UK economy.","false","Biography information for Cathy Jamieson","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Cathy Jamieson","200643"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62208","HM Treasury","false","2014-06-23","<p>When appropriately conducted, shadow banking can benefit the economy by increasing the availability of credit to a range of individuals or firms, and provide a valuable alternative to bank funding. It provides credit and liquidity to the real economy and can improve efficiency and drive innovation in the financial system through firms developing expert knowledge in a particular area.</p><p> </p><p>However, the Government is aware of the risks shadow banking activities pose to financial stability when things go wrong. The crisis showed that some shadow banking entities created pro-cyclical build-ups of leverage, did not fully transfer credit risk, were susceptible to rapid sell-offs, and were very complex. It also became clear that the shadow banking sector had very complex interconnections with the traditional banking system.</p><p> </p><p>Recognising the need to improve the transparency and supervision of the shadow banking sector, the Government has taken steps to improve the way shadow banking entities are regulated.</p><p> </p><p>Domestically, the Government has created new Financial Policy Committee (FPC) within the Bank of England to ensure emerging risks and vulnerabilities across the financial system as a whole are identified, monitored and effectively addressed. In September last year, the Committee agreed as one of its medium term priorities the identification and management of potential systemic risks from shadow banking.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>At the international level, the Government is actively supporting the effective regulation of the sector in EU policymaking, and the UK is instrumental in shaping the global regulatory response at the Financial Stability Board.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","200642 ; 200643","2014-06-23T15:19:45.4275036Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62208/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62208/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62208/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2014-06-17","Financial Services","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps his Department is taking to ensure the stability of the shadow banking sector.","false","Biography information for Cathy Jamieson","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Cathy Jamieson","200644"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62209","HM Treasury","false","2014-06-23","<p>The Government has no plans to alter the design or rules of the Equitable Life Payment Scheme, including those which relate to the level of payments. Decisions on the level of ex-gratia payments took account of the fiscal situation and wider fairness concerns across all taxpayers. The payments for different types of policyholder were made on the basis of recommendations made by the Independent Commission on Equitable Life Payments.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2014-06-23T15:50:25.8527699Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62209/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62209/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62209/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2014-06-17","Equitable Life Assurance Society: Compensation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will take steps to increase the compensation paid to Equitable Life policyholders.","false","Biography information for Mr Laurence Robertson","Tewkesbury","Mr Laurence Robertson","200648"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62210","HM Treasury","false","2014-06-24","<p>From October 2014 around 24 million people will receive a personal tax summary from HMRC setting out how their income tax and National Insurance contributions have been calculated for the previous year (2013-14) and how it contributed to public expenditure. Tax summaries will also show taxpayers their taxable income and average tax rate, allowing the individual in future to compare one year's tax record with another.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2014-06-24T16:45:37.2252656Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62210/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62210/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62210/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2014-06-17","Income Tax","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he plans to display changes to the amount of income tax levied on an individual on their end of year statement.","false","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","200661"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62211","HM Treasury","false","2014-06-23","<p>The Government believes it is important for consumers to be able to compare the cost of credit products easily.</p><p> </p><p>The Consumer Credit Directive (CCD) requires the APR to be stated in pre-contract credit information and in the credit agreement itself, as well as in advertising where triggered. In addition, firms must state the total amount payable (TAP), which is the sum of the amount borrowed and the total charge for credit (TCC).</p><p> </p><p>As the CCD is full harmonisation in the relevant areas, it is not open to Member States to require disclosure of the TCC in addition – although the consumer can work this out as the difference between the TAP and the amount borrowed. Lenders can also include the TCC on a voluntary basis.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>As previously shared with the Public Accounts Committee, the Government raised the issue of how to present cost information with the European Commission as part of its current review into the implementation of the CCD.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2014-06-23T15:54:33.4060252Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62211/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62211/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62211/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2014-06-17","Credit: Interest Rates","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will take steps to mandate that APR figures be displayed in cash terms.","false","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","200662"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62212","HM Treasury","false","2014-06-30","<p>Estimates of the numbers of individuals with self employment sources are published in HMRC's National Statistics table 3.10 which is available at the following internet address:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/income-of-individuals-with-self-employment-sources-2010-to-2011" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/income-of-individuals-with-self-employment-sources-2010-to-2011</a></p><p>The numbers of individuals making zero profits and at other income levels is also shown in these tables.</p><p> </p><p>Tables for 2009-10 and earlier years are available from the National Archives internet site at the following address:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20121102223513/http:/hmrc.gov.uk/stats/income_distribution/menu-by-year.htm" target="_blank">http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20121102223513/http:/hmrc.gov.uk/stats/income_distribution/menu-by-year.htm</a></p><p> </p><p>Overall, these show a long term trend of growth in the numbers of self-employed people.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","200630 ; 200631 ; 200633","2014-06-30T14:22:54.7255136Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62212/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62212/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62212/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2014-06-17","Self-employed: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the (a) mean and (b) median age of people registered as self-employed was in (i) Scotland and (ii) Kilmarnock and Loudoun constituency in (A) 2010, (B) 2011, (C) 2012 and (D) 2013.","false","Biography information for Cathy Jamieson","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Cathy Jamieson","200632"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62213","HM Treasury","false","2014-06-30","<p>Estimates of the numbers of individuals with self employment sources are published in HMRC's National Statistics table 3.10 which is available at the following internet address:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/income-of-individuals-with-self-employment-sources-2010-to-2011" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/income-of-individuals-with-self-employment-sources-2010-to-2011</a></p><p>The numbers of individuals making zero profits and at other income levels is also shown in these tables.</p><p> </p><p>Tables for 2009-10 and earlier years are available from the National Archives internet site at the following address:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20121102223513/http:/hmrc.gov.uk/stats/income_distribution/menu-by-year.htm" target="_blank">http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20121102223513/http:/hmrc.gov.uk/stats/income_distribution/menu-by-year.htm</a></p><p> </p><p>Overall, these show a long term trend of growth in the numbers of self-employed people.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","200630 ; 200631 ; 200632","2014-06-30T14:22:54.8150969Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62213/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62213/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62213/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2014-06-17","Self-employed: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many people were registered as self-employed in (a) Kilmarnock and Loudoun constituency and (b) Scotland in each of the last four years for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Cathy Jamieson","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Cathy Jamieson","200633"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62214","HM Treasury","false","2014-06-23","<p>The Government has consistently taken action to improve regulation of financial markets since 2010.</p><p> </p><p>The Government put in place a new architecture for financial regulation through the Financial Services Act 2012, with the aim of delivering stability, protecting consumers and enhancing the integrity of financial markets. The Financial Policy Committee in the Bank of England is responsible for protecting and enhancing financial stability, while the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prudential_Regulation_Authority" target="_blank">Prudential Regulation Authority</a> is responsible for the prudential regulation of deposit-takers, insurers and certain investment firms. The <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Financial_Conduct_Authority" target="_blank">Financial Conduct Authority</a> is responsible for protecting consumers, promoting competition, and enhancing integrity in markets.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Following findings of attempted manipulation of LIBOR in summer 2012, the Government took quick action to make the administration of, and contribution to this key financial benchmark, a regulated activity. Furthermore, on 12 June 2014 the Government announced further steps to raise standards of conduct in the financial system with a joint review by the Treasury, the Bank of England and the Financial Conduct Authority into the way wholesale financial markets operate. Led by Bank of England Deputy Governor for Markets and Banking, Minouche Shafik, the Review will run for 12 months, and will focus on those wholesale markets where the bulk of concerns about misconduct have arisen - fixed income, currency and commodity markets. The Terms of Reference for the Review have been published <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/fair-and-effective-markets-review-terms-of-reference/fair-and-effective-financial-markets-review-terms-of-reference" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/fair-and-effective-markets-review-terms-of-reference/fair-and-effective-financial-markets-review-terms-of-reference</a></p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2014-06-23T15:11:20.3758309Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62214/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62214/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62214/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2014-06-17","Financial Markets","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps he is taking to improve regulation of the UK securities market.","false","Biography information for Cathy Jamieson","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Cathy Jamieson","200646"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62215","HM Treasury","false","2014-06-26","<p> </p><p>I have been asked to reply.</p><p>The Climate Change Act (2008) commits the UK to reducing emissions of GHGs and the accompanying Impact Assessment sets out that within the context of global efforts to limit climate change the benefits to the UK will be greater than the costs. However, the department has not made specific estimates of the savings to the public purse from a move to a low carbon economy as the precise fiscal impact of carbon emission reductions will depend on the mix of policies used.</p><p> </p><p>For this reason individual assessments of the fiscal impacts of policies have been made and published where appropriate. In addition, it is worth noting that in the Coalition Agreement, the Government committed to increase the proportion of tax revenue accounted for by environmental taxes.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Bexhill and Battle","Gregory Barker",,"2014-06-26T15:47:30.094003Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62215/answer","Biography information for Lord Barker of Battle","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62215/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62215/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2014-06-17","Carbon Emissions","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate his Department has made of the savings to the public purse of reductions in carbon emissions leading to a low carbon economy.","false","Biography information for David Simpson","Upper Bann","David Simpson","200653"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62216","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2014-07-01","<p> </p><p>In March, we published new planning guidance, which local planning authorities can use when determining planning applications. It explains that planning applications are considered on their own merits and, by law, must be determined in accordance with the development plan for the area, unless material considerations indicate otherwise. The ‘Open space, sports and recreation facilities' section of the guidance addresses provision of open spaces of public value.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>More broadly, separate to the planning system, the underlying statutory duties for local (burial) authorities are outlined in the Local Authorities Cemeteries Order 1977. The associated guidance is overseen by the Ministry for Justice, and is available at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.justice.gov.uk/downloads/burials-and-coroners/burial-ground-managers.pdf" target="_blank">www.justice.gov.uk/downloads/burials-and-coroners/burial-ground-managers.pdf</a></p><p> </p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2014-07-01T15:40:52.4083155Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62216/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62216/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62216/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2014-06-17","Cemeteries: Planning Permission","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what guidance his Department has published for the use of local authorities in determining planning permission applications for the creation of cemeteries.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","200634"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62217","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-06-23","<p>The Ministry of Justice has not made an estimate of the number of grave spaces created since the introduction of the London Local Authorities Act 2007 or the number of local authorities who have used powers under the Act to re-use graves. However, as the Ministry of Justice has responsibility for burial law and policy, I am keeping the issue of burial space under active review including considering what legislative changes might be necessary to address a shortage of graves.</p>","Bermondsey and Old Southwark","Simon Hughes","200636","2014-06-23T15:43:33.8131514Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62217/answer","Biography information for Simon Hughes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62217/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62217/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-06-17","Cemeteries: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what estimate his Department has made of the number of grave spaces that have been created in London since the introduction of the London Local Authorities Act 2007.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","200635"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62218","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-06-23","<p>The Ministry of Justice has not made an estimate of the number of grave spaces created since the introduction of the London Local Authorities Act 2007 or the number of local authorities who have used powers under the Act to re-use graves. However, as the Ministry of Justice has responsibility for burial law and policy, I am keeping the issue of burial space under active review including considering what legislative changes might be necessary to address a shortage of graves.</p>","Bermondsey and Old Southwark","Simon Hughes","200635","2014-06-23T15:43:33.9077797Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62218/answer","Biography information for Simon Hughes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62218/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62218/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-06-17","Cemeteries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what estimate his Department has made of the number of local authorities which have adopted powers under the London Local Authorities Act 2007 to re-use graves where burial rights have been extinguished since that Act came into force.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","200636"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62219","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2014-06-23","<p> </p><p>Developers and internet providers recognise the importance of telephone and internet provision in new builds and that customers' expectation is these services will be available on the day they move in. My Department, with the Department for Culture, Media and Sport, is working with house builders and providers of telephone and internet services to ensure newly built residential properties have access to telephone and internet services.</p><p> </p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2014-06-23T14:04:47.4643904Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62219/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62219/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62219/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2014-06-17","Housing: ICT","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what steps he is taking to ensure that newly built residential properties have access to telephone and internet services.","false","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","201013"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62220","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2014-06-23","<p> </p><p>During 2013/14, 272 planning applications were referred to the Secretary of State under the Town and Country Planning (Consultation) (England) Direction 2009. Records indicate that the average number of days it took to make a decision was 21 days.</p><p> </p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2014-06-23T14:34:48.2197516Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62220/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62220/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62220/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2014-06-17","Planning Permission","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what average length of time is taken by his Department to make a decision on a planning application referred to it.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","201044"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62221","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2014-06-24","<p> </p><p>I am not aware of representations about landlords who own multiple properties disguising their ownership of a property when submitting a planning application.</p><p> </p><p>It is already a requirement that planning applications must be accompanied by a certificate which applicants must complete that provides certain details about the ownership of the application site. An application is not valid, and therefore cannot be determined by the local planning authority, unless the relevant certificate has been completed.</p><p> </p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles","201040","2014-06-24T11:48:20.8769181Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62221/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62221/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62221/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2014-06-17","Landlords: Planning Permission","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what representations he has received on landlords who own multiple properties disguising their ownership of a property when submitting a planning application.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","201039"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62222","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2014-06-23","<p> </p><p>We are currently considering whether to confirm a Compulsory Purchase Order known as The London Borough of Haringey (Northumberland Development Project) (No 1) submitted by Haringey Council which includes the site of 1-3 Paxton Road. The Order was received in the Department on 5 September 2012.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>This is a complex case. After the close of the inquiry there were matters in respect of which further views of the interested parties were sought and considered. This has delayed the decision in this case.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>We hope to issue the decision on this shortly. It is not appropriate to comment further as to do so may prejudice the Secretary of State's decision.</p><p> </p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles","201048","2014-06-23T14:43:19.5127845Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62222/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62222/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62222/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2014-06-17","Compulsory Purchase: Haringey","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, when his Department received the application from Haringey Council for a Compulsory Purchase Order to be issued for the site of 1-3 Paxton Road, London, N17 0PB.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","201046"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62223","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2014-06-24","<p> </p><p>I am not aware of representations about landlords who own multiple properties disguising their ownership of a property when submitting a planning application.</p><p> </p><p>It is already a requirement that planning applications must be accompanied by a certificate which applicants must complete that provides certain details about the ownership of the application site. An application is not valid, and therefore cannot be determined by the local planning authority, unless the relevant certificate has been completed.</p><p> </p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles","201039","2014-06-24T11:48:20.8049939Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62223/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62223/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62223/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2014-06-17","Landlords: Planning Permission","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will take steps to ensure that the legal owner of a property is identified when a planning application is submitted relating to that property.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","201040"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62224","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2014-06-23","<p> </p><p>Since May 2012 (when the National Planning Casework Unit took responsibility for this area of work) the average length of time to make a decision on opposed planning Compulsory Purchase Orders is 10-11 weeks.</p><p> </p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2014-06-23T14:20:31.7243326Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62224/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62224/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62224/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2014-06-17","Compulsory Purchase","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what the average length of time is taken by his Department to issue a Compulsory Purchase Order to a local authority.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","201047"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62225","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2014-06-24","<p> </p><p>Paragraph 207 of the National Planning Policy Framework sets out the policy for enforcement, and can be found at the following link:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://planningguidance.planningportal.gov.uk/blog/policy/achieving-sustainable-development/decision-taking/" target="_blank">http://planningguidance.planningportal.gov.uk/blog/policy/achieving-sustainable-development/decision-taking/</a>. The new planning guidance has a section entitled “Ensuring effective enforcement”, which can be found at the following link:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://planningguidance.planningportal.gov.uk/blog/guidance/ensuring-effective-enforcement/" target="_blank">http://planningguidance.planningportal.gov.uk/blog/guidance/ensuring-effective-enforcement/</a>. Also in August 2013 we published guidance for local authorities on dealing with illegal and unauthorised encampments, which can be found at the following link: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/dealing-with-illegal-and-unauthorised-encampments-a-summary-of-available-powers" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/dealing-with-illegal-and-unauthorised-encampments-a-summary-of-available-powers</a></p><p> </p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2014-06-24T11:46:51.7143664Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62225/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62225/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62225/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2014-06-17","Planning","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what guidance his Department has issued to local authorities on their obligations to take action against breaches of planning law.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","201041"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62226","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2014-06-23","<p> </p><p>We are currently considering whether to confirm a Compulsory Purchase Order known as The London Borough of Haringey (Northumberland Development Project) (No 1) submitted by Haringey Council which includes the site of 1-3 Paxton Road. The Order was received in the Department on 5 September 2012.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>This is a complex case. After the close of the inquiry there were matters in respect of which further views of the interested parties were sought and considered. This has delayed the decision in this case.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>We hope to issue the decision on this shortly. It is not appropriate to comment further as to do so may prejudice the Secretary of State's decision.</p><p> </p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles","201046","2014-06-23T14:43:19.3747062Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62226/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62226/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62226/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2014-06-17","Compulsory Purchase: Haringey","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, when he expects to reach a decision on whether Haringey Council will be issued with a Compulsory Purchase Order in relation to the site of 1-3 Paxton Road, London N17 0PB.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","201048"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62227","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-06-23","<p> </p><p>Only the courts have the power to impose fines on people convicted of felling trees without a licence where one is required under the Forestry Commissioners' Power to control felling of trees in Part II of the Forestry Act 1967 (as amended). This can be up to £2,500 or twice the value of the trees, whichever is the higher.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Where it appears to the Forestry Commissioners that somebody has committed an offence by felling trees without a licence where one is required, the Commissioners can serve them with a Restocking Notice requiring the area to be restocked. Failure to comply with the requirements of a Restocking Notice can result in an Enforcement Notice being issued. It is an offence not to obey an Enforcement Notice, which can mean a possible fine of up to £5,000.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Where deforestation accompanied by a change of land use has not received the required consent and has a significant impact on the environment, the Forestry Commission can, under the provisions in The Environmental Impact Assessment (Forestry)(England and Wales) Regulations 1999, issue an Enforcement Notice requiring the land to be restored to its condition before the work started.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","North Cornwall","Dan Rogerson",,"2014-06-23T10:21:26.742611Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62227/answer","Biography information for Dan Rogerson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62227/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62227/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-06-17","Forestry Commission","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what powers the Forestry Commission has to (a) impose fines, (b) restore woodland and (c) take other enforcement action where a landowner has carried out deforestation contrary to the Forestry Act 1967.","false","Biography information for Mrs Maria Miller","Basingstoke","Maria Miller","201063"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62228","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2014-06-24","<p> </p><p>We have reformed the planning system to make it simpler, more positive and faster to navigate. We have abolished top down regional planning and increased the types of development that benefit from permitted development rights. Where planning permission is required, we have stripped away unnecessary information requirements while retaining essential safeguards. The National Planning Policy Framework, and our recently published simplified planning guidance, provides a significantly clearer basis for making decisions than the confusing array of sometimes contradictory policy that we inherited; and we have taken steps to tackle under-performance by planning authorities where this occurs.</p><p> </p><p>The latest statistics show that these steps are having a significant impact. For example, district level planning authorities between January and March 2014 granted 76 per cent of major applications on time compared with 60 per cent in the same quarter in 2013.</p><p> </p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2014-06-24T11:44:59.4970813Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62228/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62228/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62228/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2014-06-17","Planning","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what recent steps he has taken to speed up the planning system.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","201045"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62229","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2014-06-23","<p>Ofcom monitors and publishes broadband coverage data for the UK indicated in its 2013 UK fixed broadband market report that superfast broadband was available to 73% of UK premises. Ofcom did not, however, publish a separate figure for the number of homes with fibre to the home broadband services.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2014-06-23T12:55:28.3014145Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62229/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62229/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62229/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2014-06-17","Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what estimate he has made of the number of homes in the UK served by fibre to the home broadband services.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","201059"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62230","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2014-06-24","<p>These arrangements are currently being finalised.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2014-06-24T09:51:36.4925108Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62230/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62230/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62230/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2014-06-17","Press","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, pursuant to the Answer of 10 June 2014, Official Report, columns 67-8W, on the press, whether he has set a date for meeting victims of press abuse and their representatives.","false","Biography information for Bill Wiggin","North Herefordshire","Bill Wiggin","201081"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62231","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2014-06-23","<p>DCMS has not issued a formal response to the letter of 2 May 2014. The letter has been passed to the planning authorities as part of that process.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2014-06-23T12:57:35.4357619Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62231/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62231/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62231/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2014-06-17","UNESCO","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, if he will place in the Library a copy of his Department's response to the letter of 2 May 2014 from Mr Kishore Rao, the Director of the UNESCO Culture Sector, World Heritage Centre.","false","Biography information for Sir Christopher Chope","Christchurch","Mr Christopher Chope","201110"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62232","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2014-06-23","<p>The Dorset and East Devon Coast World Heritage Site continues to enjoy World Heritage status and it is not currently under threat. The UK Government takes its responsibilities to conserve World Heritage Sites very seriously. The planning systems in place provide robust processes for assessing the potential impact of proposals on heritage assets and dealing appropriately with them.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2014-06-23T12:58:19.7530692Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62232/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62232/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62232/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2014-06-17","World Heritage Sites: South West","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what steps his Department is taking to ensure that the Dorset and East Devon coast continues to enjoy World Heritage status and remains in compliance with Article 4 of the World Heritage Convention; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Christopher Chope","Christchurch","Mr Christopher Chope","201128"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62233","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2014-06-24","<p>Work has been ongoing in Herefordshire to search for appropriate locations for potential masts, and for each mast to: come to an agreement with a landlord, find an option to transmit signal back into the existing mobile networks, and ensure that the mast can be connected to a source of electricity</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2014-06-24T09:46:10.5012476Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62233/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62233/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62233/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2014-06-17","Mobile Phones: Herefordshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what progress has been made on the Mobile Infrastructure Project in Herefordshire.","false","Biography information for Bill Wiggin","North Herefordshire","Bill Wiggin","201150"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62234","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2014-06-24","<p>The Mobile Infrastructure Project has faced challenges in finding ways to connect signal from masts back into the existing networks, and DCMS officials are assessing the impact of these challenges on overall progress and schedules.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2014-06-24T09:48:37.0229567Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62234/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62234/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62234/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2014-06-17","Mobile Phones: Herefordshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, whether the Mobile Infrastructure Project in Herefordshire is on course to be delivered on schedule.","false","Biography information for Bill Wiggin","North Herefordshire","Bill Wiggin","201151"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62235","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2014-06-24","<p>Notspot data is compiled and held by Ofcom, with information provided by the Mobile Network Operators. In areas where coverage is thought to be marginal, or there is uncertainty over coverage, DCMS officials have commissioned drive testing to check the level of coverage.</p><p> </p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2014-06-24T09:50:18.628416Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62235/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62235/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62235/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2014-06-17","Mobile Phones","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what the criteria are by which Arqiva assesses notspot data.","false","Biography information for Bill Wiggin","North Herefordshire","Bill Wiggin","201152"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62236","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2014-06-24","<p>DCMS officials provided Arqiva with the latest data on notspots, updated by Ofcom for 2014 with information from the Mobile Network Operators. This shows that coverage has improved in Fownhope since the inception of the project. The Mobile Infrastructure Project can intervene in areas where there is no mobile coverage from any operator, and where the cost of the build of a mast, considered alongside the numbers of premises that would benefit from the additional coverage, provides value for money. Unfortunately this is no longer the case for the proposed mast location in Fownhope, and Arqiva made a recommendation to officials to not proceed.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2014-06-24T09:53:26.2218973Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62236/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62236/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62236/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2014-06-17","Mobile Phones: Herefordshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what the process was by which Arqiva arrived at its decision not to proceed with the proposed Fownhope mast.","false","Biography information for Bill Wiggin","North Herefordshire","Bill Wiggin","201153"
